<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-137-230  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 137 230.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Feb 5 1990 n576 p104(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Technology Randamp;D offsets defense cuts; winners under Bush budgetinclude NIST, NSF, Energy. (1991 budget, includes a relatedarticle on NASA's 1991 budget.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Nostrand, Jim Van.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Bush administration's 1991 budget will see cuts indefense-related spending, but the good news fortechnology-oriented companies is that the reductions will be madeup for with increased civilian research and development spending.andO;The Department of Defense budget will increase to $295.1 billion,2.6 percent less than the inflation rate.andP;  Increases in otherareas include; NASA, up 23 percent to $15.13 billion; NationalInstitute of Science and Technology, up 21 percent, to $198million; National Science Foundation, up 14 percent, to $2.4billion; Energy Department research, up nearly 14 percent, $2.3billion; space station Freedom, up 45 percent, to $2.45 billion;air-traffic control upgrades, up 45 percent, to $2.5 billion; andthe superconducting super collider, up 45 percent, to $318million.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     BudgetingGovernment FundingResearch and DevelopmentNational GovernmentMilitary.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Programs terminated in the FY 1991 budget. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>